00:09:27.549 --> 00:09:30.599
So I'll give you a little overview of
what you missed.

00:09:31.679 --> 00:09:35.959
Again you take a Mac out of the box, you open
it up, it needs a place to put your stuff.

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:37.320
We'll call that a local home.

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:41.050
And that's going to be automatically created
in the users folder on your machine.

00:09:41.049 --> 00:09:46.379
And Mac OS X will create subfolders for you: Your
documents folder, your library folder, et cetera.

00:09:46.379 --> 00:09:49.000
In the library folder is a preferences folder.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:54.470
And in the preferences folder are where
your application preferences are stored.

00:09:54.470 --> 00:09:56.759
This is fantastic but it's not necessarily scalable.

00:09:56.759 --> 00:10:03.370
It defaults to /users and it's very easy to
use because that's what we do out of the box.

00:10:03.370 --> 00:10:07.090
It's the default way of creating home
folders on Mac OS X. It's tested.

00:10:07.090 --> 00:10:09.120
All the developers that are here at this session

00:10:09.120 --> 00:10:13.909
that are writing your applications are most likely
testing against this situation, this scenario.

00:10:13.909 --> 00:10:18.539
And it's uniform so those of you users who have
Macs at home are used to using their Mac that way

00:10:18.539 --> 00:10:21.159
when they go to work it will be the same way.

00:10:21.159 --> 00:10:22.819
But it doesn't scale very well.

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:27.740
For one thing there's no separation between
the operating system and your user data.

00:10:27.740 --> 00:10:34.159
So your user home folder's on that same volume
as your operating system, called the boot volume.

00:10:34.159 --> 00:10:37.149
And some of you may want to set up a system whereby

00:10:37.149 --> 00:10:41.069
that operating system can be replaced
without losing use you are data.

00:10:41.070 --> 00:10:45.280
I imagine most of you want to be able to replace
the operating system without losing user data.

00:10:45.279 --> 00:10:49.679
And there are some mechanisms in Mac
OS X for doing that, but not quickly.

00:10:49.679 --> 00:10:58.479
And so partitioning your drive and kind of having a boot
OS and a user volume may be an approach that you like.

00:10:58.480 --> 00:11:06.500
Some of you are work around that by creating a symbolic link
from /users on the startup drive to the secondary drive.

00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:12.669
And others of you actually edit the FSFS
tab file so that that second volume gets mounted sort

00:11:12.669 --> 00:11:17.409
of invisibly behind the scenes on the first volume.

00:11:17.409 --> 00:11:22.149
We'll show you in a moment maybe a better way
of doing that, a more easily supportable way.

00:11:22.149 --> 00:11:25.199
And then the other downside is all
the users data is on one hard disk.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:29.690
So if their MacBook Pro gets stolen or lost

00:11:29.690 --> 00:11:35.190
or the hard drive crashes they lose all
their data, and they may come crying to you.

00:11:35.190 --> 00:11:40.170
So you may work around this by saying let's give everyone
a network home and we'll have everything on a server

00:11:40.169 --> 00:11:43.929
and we can back up the server and
we can put it on redundant storage.

00:11:43.929 --> 00:11:45.899
And that works great.

00:11:45.899 --> 00:11:51.980
Typically you'll locate that on a share point
on a file server like an AFP, SMB or NFS share.

00:11:51.980 --> 00:11:56.920
The beauty of this is none of the user's
data exists on their local computer.

00:11:56.919 --> 00:11:59.500
It's used live over the network,
and that means it's portable.

00:11:59.500 --> 00:12:05.980
You can go from any machine, go to any machine
on your network and get to your user environment.

00:12:05.980 --> 00:12:08.170
The downside to this is performance.

00:12:08.169 --> 00:12:12.809
All the reads and rights to a user's
home folder are going over the LAN.

00:12:12.809 --> 00:12:17.299
That means cache files are going over the LAN as people
are browsing websites, all of these temporary files

00:12:17.299 --> 00:12:23.240
that are supposed to speed up access and take a load off
the network are actually traveling twice over your network.

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:28.210
If people start to capture digital video in
iMovie to their desktop it's going over your LAN.

00:12:28.210 --> 00:12:29.100
So downside there.

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:33.560
And also it's not ideal for portable because the moment
you unplug you have no access to your home folder.

00:12:33.559 --> 00:12:38.349
So we'll represent it with this picture and we'll tell
you for portables not to necessarily a good approach

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:41.659
but we'll discuss in a moment how
you might use this in conjunction

00:12:41.659 --> 00:12:46.399
with portable homes to get the best of both worlds.

00:12:46.399 --> 00:12:51.730
So a portable home, like with Directory
Services is a mechanism

00:12:51.730 --> 00:12:54.050
that will synchronize what's on
the network and what's on your disk.

00:12:54.049 --> 00:12:58.339
So you have a local home on your machine
and a network home folder as well.

00:12:58.340 --> 00:13:01.639
And you're going to periodically sync,
synchronize all of that data.

00:13:01.639 --> 00:13:04.720
So you should have a copy in both places.

00:13:04.720 --> 00:13:08.430
The beauty of this is you can use it offline, you
can work at home, you can work in another office,

00:13:08.429 --> 00:13:14.539
you can work in the airport; but you can backup the
version of the user's data that's on your server.

00:13:14.539 --> 00:13:17.370
It's all in one place so it's easier to get to

00:13:18.399 --> 00:13:21.459
And again, you can get to it from
multiple connected systems on your LAN.

00:13:21.460 --> 00:13:25.700
So the portable home is a periodic sync of your
home folder and if you've got the mobile account

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:28.980
which typically the two are used
together, then you can be somewhat assured

00:13:28.980 --> 00:13:34.180
that the user's environment can travel with them.

00:13:34.179 --> 00:13:40.120
Now, one things go wrong you may want tips
on troubleshooting these portable homes

00:13:40.120 --> 00:13:42.990
and one that I'll point you to
is something that some of you ran

00:13:42.990 --> 00:13:49.419
into where you configure home synchronization
using the Workgroup Manager tool.

00:13:49.419 --> 00:13:54.209
And it's synchronizing, maybe you want to stop doing
that and you in Workgroup Manager set it to never,

00:13:54.210 --> 00:13:56.360
thinking that will mean never synchronize your home folder.

00:13:56.360 --> 00:14:01.590
That actually just means never control
the synchronization of your home folder.

00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:06.840
So we do have a tech note that explains
how to change that if necessary.

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:10.460
And also you should know that the process
that's actually doing the synchronization

00:14:10.460 --> 00:14:12.320
in the background is called Mirror Agent.

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:17.730
And you're able to enable a debug mode in
Mirror Agent using the defaults command.

00:14:17.730 --> 00:14:25.590
Set a preference for Mirror Agent, and there
are increasing levels of detail from 1 to 4.

00:14:25.590 --> 00:14:30.210
Now you may find that a portable home works great
for some situation, and a network home works great

00:14:30.210 --> 00:14:34.370
for other situations and you want to be able to use both.

00:14:34.370 --> 00:14:39.720
An example would be somebody that who sits at a
desktop machine most of the time, perhaps an engineer,

00:14:39.720 --> 00:14:45.170
they're working on a big screen and a beefy
Mac Pro, but they occasionally travel.

00:14:45.169 --> 00:14:51.169
Or they want to take some work home, right?

00:14:51.169 --> 00:14:56.679
So set them up with a network home on their desktop machine
and when they want to check out a MacBook or MacBook Pro

00:14:56.679 --> 00:15:00.019
that can be set up with a portable home
so they can take a version with them.

00:15:00.019 --> 00:15:04.460
When they return to the office they can resynchronize
that and then go back to their network hope.

00:15:04.460 --> 00:15:06.540
The opposite is also possible.

00:15:06.539 --> 00:15:09.480
You could have professors that have
a portable that they travel with,

00:15:09.480 --> 00:15:11.340
and that's the machine they use at home and in the office.

00:15:11.340 --> 00:15:17.000
But when it gets time to go walk into the lecture hall to
deliver their content, rather than unplugging everything

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:22.570
on that portable machine, carrying it into the lecture
hall, and reconnecting audio and video and networking

00:15:22.570 --> 00:15:27.050
and maybe even USB, you can have a desktop
