But it had a lot of crucial data on it and he was
able to use his portable home to resynchronize that.

00:50:01.590 --> 00:50:05.079
I had an opposite experience, or a
near opposite experience with Frank.

00:50:05.079 --> 00:50:13.110
I was fooling around with portable home directories day
one in 10.40, and I didn't think the synchronization

00:50:13.110 --> 00:50:17.950
of happening properly so I deleted a bunch of
files on the server so I could resynchronize.

00:50:17.949 --> 00:50:24.359
And so then my machine said oh well it changed the
network version sooner and these folders are gone

00:50:24.360 --> 00:50:27.960
so it removed my iPhoto library from my desktop machine.

00:50:27.960 --> 00:50:32.679
Six years worth of pictures of my kids from, like, day zero.

00:50:32.679 --> 00:50:33.799
That was on ugly scenario.

00:50:33.800 --> 00:50:37.690
And I didn't actually discover that for about three
months, because the cache files were still there.

00:50:37.690 --> 00:50:41.500
So iPhoto looked fine, but the
photos behind there were gone.

00:50:41.500 --> 00:50:45.340
Luckily I made a backup before I started that,
and you want to make sure you do the same.

00:50:45.340 --> 00:50:51.559
Back up the server and make sure that
your clients are in fact synchronizing.

00:50:51.559 --> 00:50:52.820
So there's a little bit of a danger here.

00:50:52.820 --> 00:50:54.410
If you're only backing up their network home

00:50:54.409 --> 00:50:58.409
and their portable home is not synchronizing
to that, you're not getting everything.

00:50:58.409 --> 00:51:02.960
But the beauty of this approach is you're deploying
an Enterprise backup solution at the server side

00:51:02.960 --> 00:51:09.849
and you're sort of letting the clients come
and go and update their files as they do that.

00:51:09.849 --> 00:51:12.659
So if you want to make sure you get
everything you might want to push some

00:51:12.659 --> 00:51:15.349
of the responsibility for backup onto your users.

00:51:15.349 --> 00:51:20.829
And you can do that by way of client side backup
app lay indications like the .Mac backup tool.

00:51:20.829 --> 00:51:25.069
You have to have a .Mac subscription
to use it -- it's about $99 a year --

00:51:25.070 --> 00:51:31.210
but it doesn't just back up to your .Mac iDisk,
which is about 1 gigabyte worth of online storage.

00:51:31.210 --> 00:51:34.340
It'll also back up to optical disks, CDs, and DVDs.

00:51:34.340 --> 00:51:38.480
It'll back up to a network server,
it's back up to your iPod.

00:51:38.480 --> 00:51:43.250
It'll pop up a very inobtrusive reminder, hey, it's
time to do your monthly backup, give me a disk.

00:51:43.250 --> 00:51:48.679
You give it a disk, it burns the disk, it spits
it out, and it says write this on the disk.

00:51:48.679 --> 00:51:55.409
So very easy for end users to use and puts a little bit
more of the responsibility on their shoulders and covers you

00:51:55.409 --> 00:51:59.399
in case that synchronization isn't
getting all of their files.

00:51:59.400 --> 00:52:06.289
You can also consider using things like iSync and .Mac Sync
to put contacts and calendar information on people's phones,

00:52:06.289 --> 00:52:12.230
on people's iPods, or on other
computers by way of .Mac Sync.

00:52:12.230 --> 00:52:16.789
This isn't a full backup, obviously, but if you lose
your phone and some of you probably support people

00:52:16.789 --> 00:52:21.460
that have their entire contact list in their phone
you've got a backup on your machine and vice versa.

00:52:21.460 --> 00:52:23.970
And then .Mac Sync will let you
do this with multiple computers

00:52:23.969 --> 00:52:27.439
and will even handle things like
bookmarks and mail settings.

00:52:27.440 --> 00:52:32.019
So if you use iMap for your mail you don't
need to worry about synchronizing Mail,

00:52:32.019 --> 00:52:39.000
but you might want to synchronize the Mail rules and the
signatures, and the smart mailboxes and that sort of thing.

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:42.400
And then, of course, new in Leopard
is the Time Machine backup tool.

00:52:42.400 --> 00:52:46.519
And this is going to perform backup
for you in two primary ways.

00:52:46.519 --> 00:52:49.090
One being backup to an external disk.

00:52:49.090 --> 00:52:53.960
So assign it your users an external hard drive
and tell them this is your backup solution,

00:52:53.960 --> 00:52:58.039
plug it in and it will copy your
data onto this external disk.

00:52:58.039 --> 00:53:05.170
Or set up a file server share point with Leopard
Server so that they can back up over the network.

00:53:05.170 --> 00:53:08.030
And you can use this in conjunction with portable homes,

00:53:08.030 --> 00:53:11.080
or you might decide that this is the
way you want to do all of your backups.

00:53:11.079 --> 00:53:15.400
So we had a great Time Machine in-depth session and
a storage solution session that you'd probably need

00:53:15.400 --> 00:53:17.269
if you're going to do all of these network backups.

00:53:17.269 --> 00:53:22.869
