a couple of tips that might, that you might not know about.

00:53:31.969 --> 00:53:34.279
And we'll start with something called PM set.

00:53:34.280 --> 00:53:39.070
So I think I showed you that in Energy Saver
you could govern -- maybe I did, maybe I didn't.

00:53:39.070 --> 00:53:44.059
In Workgroup Manager and Energy Saver management you
can govern the behavior of your portable machines.

00:53:44.059 --> 00:53:46.099
When do they spin down their hard drive?

00:53:46.099 --> 00:53:49.969
Do they turn off the display?

00:53:49.969 --> 00:53:52.149
At what point do you sleep the machine?

00:53:52.150 --> 00:53:55.720
You can do this manually if you like using the PM set tool.

00:53:55.719 --> 00:53:57.909
The PM stands for "power management."

00:53:57.909 --> 00:54:03.639
And Richard Glaser has a great
writeup on this on the MacEnterprise.org website.

00:54:03.639 --> 00:54:06.489
Also Kickstart.

00:54:06.489 --> 00:54:11.289
I've got -- I have one colleague who has a customer
that deployed a bunch of machines and they were worried

00:54:11.289 --> 00:54:18.019
that theres who were administrators on their
machines would disable the Remote Desktop client.

00:54:18.019 --> 00:54:21.780
So they figured the way to do that is
they'd go to sharing and uncheck the box.

00:54:21.780 --> 00:54:25.970
Well, unbeknownst to them behind the scenes
is a script on a schedule that looks to see

00:54:25.969 --> 00:54:31.219
if their Remote Desktop client is running, and
if it's not it uses Kickstart to start it up.

00:54:31.219 --> 00:54:36.959
So you have this mechanism to manage the machines even if
there's some effort on the remote side to prevent that.

00:54:36.960 --> 00:54:45.190
And there's one command that I use over ask over and over
to enable all access privileges for my administrator user.

00:54:45.190 --> 00:54:49.659
And I'm very thankful that in the help for
Kickstart, which you will get by type,

00:54:49.659 --> 00:54:54.019
by running the K star command
followed by dash H. They have an example after about six

00:54:54.019 --> 00:54:58.489
or seven pages worth of great documentation
of the line you use to do this.

00:54:58.489 --> 00:55:00.389
And the user they use is bob.

00:55:00.389 --> 00:55:04.859
So if you can remember to gret for bob
you can run this one command down here

00:55:04.860 --> 00:55:10.160
and get that one line you're going to use over and over.

00:55:10.159 --> 00:55:11.489
I mentioned DSCL before.

00:55:11.489 --> 00:55:14.629
The Directory Services command line will let
you navigate through your directory service.

00:55:14.630 --> 00:55:19.269
And this is your local directory, this is Active
Directory, this is Open Directory, just about anything.

00:55:19.269 --> 00:55:21.389
Read and modifier those files.

00:55:21.389 --> 00:55:24.789
It's also great tool for change
passwords from the command line.

00:55:24.789 --> 00:55:27.750
There's a man page for DSCL.

00:55:27.750 --> 00:55:35.909
DS Edit Group is a Directory Services tool that
you may like if you want to make your users

00:55:35.909 --> 00:55:44.569
who are using a nest network account or portable home, you
want to make them administrator of their local machine.

00:55:44.570 --> 00:55:49.309
So you assign them to a group in your
network directory called administrators.

00:55:49.309 --> 00:55:54.590
But the way you give those people
local admin access is you need to add

00:55:54.590 --> 00:55:59.309
that network group to the local administrators group.

00:55:59.309 --> 00:56:02.960
And I've got a couple of lines you can run one
after the other with DS edit group that'll do that.

00:56:02.960 --> 00:56:04.840
If you've got users that want to be
able to run sudo

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:07.890
from the command line this is the way you do it.

00:56:07.889 --> 00:56:13.049
In Leopard actually, group management is sort of the
build in to the UI so you don't need to fall back

00:56:13.050 --> 00:56:14.560
on the command line method for doing that.

00:56:14.559 --> 00:56:18.619
And you can also use Workgroup Manager, by the
way, to make these changes on your local machine.

00:56:18.619 --> 00:56:21.339
